</li>
</ol>
<h5> To convert scientific notation to decimal form:</h5>
<p>Step 1. Determine the exponent, \(n\), on the factor of 10.</p>
<p>Step 2. Move the decimal \(n\) places, adding zeros if needed.</p>
<ul>
<li> If the exponent is positive, move the decimal point \(n\) places to the right. </li>
<li> If the exponent is negative, move the decimal point \(n\) places to the left. </li>
</ul>
<p>Step 3. Check.</p>
<p>Example: Write in decimal form:</p>
<ol class="os-raise-noindent">
<li> \(6.2 \times 10^3\) <br/>
<strong>Solution: </strong><br/><img alt="A table explains 6.2 times 10 to the power of 3. The exponent is 3; move decimal right 3 places to get 6200; add zeros for placeholders; final answer is 6,200." src="https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/6015238e3522b3a2162047fae197819645a94470" width="550"/>
</li>
<br/>
<li> \(-8.9\times10^{-2}\) <br/>
<strong>Solution: </strong><br/><img alt="A table explaining how to write negative 8.9 times ten to the power of negative 2 in decimal form, showing the process of moving the decimal point two places left to get negative 0.089, and noting the exponent is negative 2." src="https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/a4f3a281bc009fcf08f2c70fee42aa2dfcd9cddc" width="550"/>
</li>
</ol>
